description: Hordeum leporinum has fairly robust heads measuring about 2 cm in diameter. At each node, the lateral pair of spikelets are as well developed as is the central one, analogous to the condition in six-row barley. description: Note large size with thick neck; dark brown head/neck; yellow-brown rump patch.

This looks like a CGS to me. In addition to geographic location, note the blunt snout; dark brown dorsal/ventral surfaces with brass marbling; costal grooves; long, laterally compressed tail. I found about a half dozen of these in a perennial woodland stream near the coast. In its terrestrial stage, this is the largest salamander in North America.

Note cream dorsal coloration (juvenile); light stripe extending diagonally from behind the eye to the corner of the mouth; dark blotches on the sides; rings near tail. This is the only documented species to occur within YNP. "Northern Pacific" ssp. (Crotalus o. oreganus).

In additional to location, note the dark red dorsal coloration with lighter ventral surface; yellow eyes; lighter coloration on snout; absence of costal grooves. This is one of the four Pacific newt species that contains a neurotoxin (tetrodoxin) throughout its body and skin membranes that can paralyze or kill vertebrates. I found about a dozen of these moving between vernal pools. 3,950'.

Note two black neck collars encircling pinkish central collar; light brown dorsal color with numerous small scattered spots. The similar-looking "Eastern" and "Sonoran" spp. do not appear to occur in JTNP.
Note slim build; smooth scales; black saddles down back with reddish flecks in between.

Note yellowish-tan dorsal coloration; white below with no markings; single row of wide, dark-edged brown blotches that extend down back; dark brown bar that crosses the crown just forward of the eyes and extends diagonally down to the corner of the mouth; smooth scales with distinctive glossy appearance. Geographically, this is probably â€œdesertâ€ ssp. (Arizona. e. eburnata).
Note the dorsal pattern of alternating bands of black and white, with white bands widest near belly. This one suffered a mortal injury on the road but was still alive.

Note S-shaped posture; hornlike supraoculars; dark eye stripe; cream dorsolateral color with brown blotches down back; Keeled scales (slightly visible). I found this one while moonlighting the roads in Joshua Tree NP.
observed stretched out on rock.

Note slim build; smooth scales; black saddles down back with reddish flecks in between; whitish belly. This species is crepuscular and nocturnal. I found this one while moonlighting the roads in Joshua Tree NP.
Note light brown color with no pattern; smooth and shiny skin with folds at bends.

I found these in a burn at 3600 feet near grizzly flat. The burn area was very large and I found at least 30 patches of morels in the two hours I was there, I was picking almost constantly until the sun went down. Most of them were dried in place, I got about 50 fresh ones and hundreds of dried ones. They seemed to be fruiting best under the pines with the shorter needles (about 3 inches long, maybe a sugar pine). The burn happened about two years ago. Although I parked in the most obvious place I didn’t see any footprints or evidence of other pickers.

For many years, an American Dipper made her nest on the side of the fishhouse.

We enjoyed watching her through the window as she'd swim and dive. She'd toss her babies' eggshells and white castings into the channel in front of the window, and one year a chick ended up in there, too.

Unfortunately, we had a huge winter and she decided to move her nest to a place that was great while the snowbanks lasted, but which failed after they melted.

Hopefully, a dipper will nest here again!

I was walking up the fire trail when I heard this thrush calling that sounded an awful lot like a Veery.  When I attended the last Christmas Bird Count, it was a pretty big deal when someone reported sighting a Veery in this area, so I was intrigued but skeptical.  The more I listened, though, the more I realized it was a kind of rising spiral of notes, as opposed to the Veery's falling cascade of notes, so I figured it was probably another thrush.  Sure enough, Sibley describes the song of the Swainson's as "similar to a Veery, but rising."  Hooray for learning a new bird song!

I saw this slug while birding the Bulb with Sarah a few weeks ago, except it was raining and I didn't have a camera. This time I went out just for the slug. Found it in exactly the same place... and then found a billion more. I must have seen at least 100 in the enclosed pond at the end of the Bulb. Madness. Still haven't made up my mind about the species. Looks a lot like the pics of both H. japonica and H. vesicula. Update: upon consulting some more photos and noting the orange dots on periostracum (the membrane surround the shell), I'm pretty sure this is Haminoea vesicula.

I turned this rock with TONS of sea spiders writhing underneath. As far as I'm concerned, sea spiders are pretty close to being the creepiest-looking animals on the planet, and yet they are awesome (mostly due to their creepiness), so I felt an odd mixture of delight and revulsion. Sort of like laughing and throwing up at the same time (except not really). I'm puzzling over the species here. I know it's not Pycnogonum, the only other genus I've ever seen, because it has palps. Given this list and the pics and descriptions in Light's, I think Ammothea hilgendorfi seems like a possibility, but my pics aren't really good enough to count segments. There definitely aren't chelae (though there might be chelifores), and it did have ovigers. Found in the San Francisco Bay, Albany Bulb, Albany, CA, swarming with many others under a rock.
